Updating The Tracker:
Progress on the Path is fully automatic and monitors gameplay completion using a system of background monitors while you are getting on with your whirling, twirling and bee hive burning.

Background monitoring comes with a few options in the Mod Menu for you to play with and customize to your liking. You are able to customize the frequency with which the background monitor will update the player and also suppress / enable notifications for the different tracking categories you are interested in being updated about. There are also several other ways Progress on the Path can be updated:

While Meditating - With the 'Perform A Full Update When Meditating' option enabled, the tracker will perform a full update automatically when the player starts meditation, the update will only run once per meditation session.

Hotkey - The update hotkey (Default NumPad 5) can be used to run a full update whenever you like, a notification will display on-screen after the update which can also be customized in the mod menu.

Progress Previews:
You can preview your current completion progress by hitting the configurable hotkey (default Numpad 6) or by selecting one of the preview entries in the glossary section.

Depending on your settings in the mod menu, the previews will display the tracked entries with specific tags attached.

Missable entries will appear under their own sub category.

The (Mod Added) tag will be applied to all entries being dynamically tracked from supported mods.

The (In Progress) tag will be applied to all quests that are active in the players journal.

The (Completed) tag will be applied to all entries that have been completed / collected.

The (Ignored) tag will be applied to any entries that have been manually set as ignored. The mod will never automatically set an option to ignored, you can use this to hide / ignore entries you don't have any interest in.

The previews will also display the names of any filters you have enabled in the mod menu at the top of the preview under the header.

Item Tracking:
Progress on the Path supports dynamic tracking of over 350 rare, unique or otherwise difficult to find items as well as hundreds of Mod Added items available from the different supported mods.

The background monitoring system will evaluate all items as they are added to your inventory or stash and update them accordingly in the previews if they are collectable.

Dropping or selling collectable items will not affect their completion status in the tracker so feel free to do whatever you want with them after collecting them for the first time.

Gwent Card Tracking:
Progress on the Path tracks all collectable Gwent Cards in its own preview message. As well as displaying a list of all cards, the preview also contains sublists categorizing the cards on how they are obtained.

Quest Tracking:
Quest tracking is quite simple under the hood. The background monitoring system will automatically update tracked quests to their correct status as you start and complete them in the game.

If there is a quest you are not able to do due to in-game decisions or some other reason, you can manually toggle the quest as 'Completed' or 'Ignored' using console commands which will be explained in the 'Console Commands' Section.

World Map Tracking:
World Map Tracking does exactly what the name suggests, as you play and discover signposts, blow up monster nests and gorge on places of power, the background monitoring system will update them and show periodic notifications (if enabled) telling you what's updating as your playing.

Notifications:
Progress on the Path comes with quite a sophisticated Notification system. You can configure the text colour, font size and a few other things in the mod menu or just disable notifications all together if you're not interested in what's being updated.

Console Commands:
Progress on the Path comes with a very handy console command to aid you as you are playing, the command is:

pt_changestatus()

As the name suggests, this command will allow you to change the status of any entry in any of the preview messages by simply passing a couple of parameters with the command.

The first parameter is the 'Unique Identifier' of the entry. This can be seen by enabling the 'Show Entry UUID's' option in the Mod Menu.

The second parameter is the new 'Status' you want the entry to adopt, you write this is an enum so it should be typed as completed, ignored, or left blank to restore the entry to its default 'Not Completed' status.

As an example:
pt_changestatus(XD1452, ignored) would update the entry to 'Ignored'
pt_changestatus(XD1452, completed) would update the entry to 'Completed'
pt_changestatus(XD1452) would revert the entry to 'Not Started'.
